description: Not all 1950's comics were full of super heroes, occult mysteries or star spanning adventures. Some were gentle kids fantasy titles like Peter Panda. Starting with a 1st issue drawn by Rube Grossman and believed to be written by Sy Reit, Peter and his friends Dronald Dragon and Jimmy and Janie Jones embarked on a 31 issue series of escapades. Peter abd his friends rarely met actual bad guys; rather harmless schemers like Foxy Dan. Most stories are fractured fairy tales or funny animal capers with many involving dragons from Dronald's neighborhood - which, reinforcing the series' kid friendliness - wasn't too far from Mother Goose's house.
name: Peter Panda

description: The world of best-selling author Sherrilyn Kenyon’s dark spin on the Arthurian mythos returns in this adaptation of the second book of the Lords of Avalon series! Varian duFey may be the son of evil Adonai sorceress Narishka duFey, but he turned his dark heritage to the side of good, acting as Avalon’s most deadly assassin. Though hated and mistrusted by the other knights whose cause he shares, when someone begins killing Grail Knights, Merlin sends her darkest knight on a quest that leads him directly to his mother’s door… and to a hag named Merewyn, who is more than she seems.
name: Lords of Avalon: Knight of Darkness

description: This comic is is a personal account of 9/11 and how the events unfolded to Linsner himself and the days follow the events. Purchases of this book helped Linsner.com donate $10,000 to the American Red Cross following the events of September 11th. There is an extended  written piece by Eva Hopkins called Homefires Burning on the last page.
name: I Love New York

description: The peaceful, bucolic morning in the city dawns like every other, until the first body is found, brutally murdered and left as a bloody sign of the dark changes to come. Who is the dead man? What dread future does his death foretell? And can even a mystically empowered champion stand against the black power that seeks to destroy a city that has never had to fight for itself? Jade Fire will have to find the answers or she and everyone she loves is doomed.
name: Jade Fire

description:
This mini-series is continued from the events of "X-Men: Deadly Genesis" and "Rise and Fall of the Shi'ar Empire" and the X-Men: Emperor Vulcan mini-series.

The X-Men have been defeated. Havok , Polaris and the Starjammers are being held and tortured in the most secure prison in the universe. Marvel Girl, Korvus and Lilandra are being hunted by the Imperial Guard. Vulcan is Emperor of the Shi’Ar Empire and his expansion has begun. No King will stand when Vulcan and his armies are done. Join Christopher Yost (X-FORCE) and Dustin Weaver (Star Wars:KOTR) as they spin the story of a fight against insurmountable odds. Do not miss this mini-series that will change the shape of the Universe and pave the way for the War of Kings.

Collected in War of Kings Omnibus.
name: X-Men: Kingbreaker

description:
The Terminator is back as Dynamite once again puts John Connor up against Skynet and the dark future as envisioned in the blockbuster films! Helmed again by writer Simon Furman, joined by artist Lui (Red Sonja) Antonio and cover artists Richard (Dark Tower) Isanove and Stjepan Sejic (covers are 50/50 ratio), "Revolution" tells a story set in the dark future of the Terminators and the present day where John Connor and his mother Sarah are on the run from the enemies sent against them from the future!

NOTE: Indicia titled as "Terminator: Revolution"

description: Completely disregard the whole Top Cow branding with this one…As there is no cheesecake or voluptuous women stalking the panels of this comic. In fact, Impaler (a new ongoing to a previous mini) provides a heaping portion of dread, action and nail biting suspense. Harms’ spin on the whole vampire mythos, making Vlad the good guy (well, good is a relative thing) who’s hunting down the horde of evil that have invaded the world, works fantastically well, as does the photo realistic artwork. A definite recommend on all fronts.
name: Impaler

description:
A brilliant reimagining of the vampire myth thanks to William Harms and artist Nick Marinkovich.

Note: Only issues #1-3 were released as print issues, eventually #4-6 were released in the Impaler trade paperback and then later the unpublished three issues were released as digital issues.
name: Impaler

description:
A History Of Violence follows the story of a small town soda shop owner by the name of Tom Mckenna. In an unfortunate turn of events, two wanted killers stumble into Tom's shop demanding money and have every intention of killing Tom. A couple of seconds later one of the killers is dead and the other is intensive care. Tom becomes an instant hero and is thrown into the public eye. Too bad for Tom the past never dies, and his deep dark past is revealed, and the law-abiding, mild mannered Tom Mckenney turns out to be some much more...

Originally published by DC through Paradox Press (under Paradox Graphic Mystery) in May 1997. This second edition was published through DC's Vertigo imprint. In 2011 a new edition was published under Vertigo Crime.
name: A History of Violence
The Adventures of Baron Munchausen
